{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4b8df9a8-f643-48e5-9404-753d59bb6bf0","content":"To switch from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform with MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0, you just need to **remove** (or set to `false`) the `<UseVSTest>` property:\n\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <!-- Remove this line (or set to false): -->\n    <!-- <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest> -->\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Why this is enough:** Starting with MSTest.Sdk 3.4+, Microsoft.Testing.Platform is the **default** runner. Setting `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` was explicitly opting out of it. Removing that property lets the SDK use its default.\n\n**Other things to be aware of:**\n\n1. **CLI change** — Run tests with `dotnet test` as before, but you can also use `dotnet run` directly on the test project (the new platform produces an executable).\n2. **Command-line filters** — The filter syntax changes slightly (e.g., `--filter` → `--filter` still works, but platform-native syntax is `--treenode-filter`).\n3. **Extensions** — If you use `.runsettings` features (data collectors, loggers), check that equivalent Microsoft.Testing.Platform extensions are referenced. Common ones (code coverage, TRX reporting) are available as NuGet packages like `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport`.\n4. **CI integration** — Ensure your CI uses the updated `dotnet test` experience or invokes the test host directly.\n\nNo other project file changes are required for a basic migration.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4223e158-3f69-4f91-83e8-9ff49297283f","outputTokens":395,"requestId":"BC22:223B6B:1C2A7AC:1F3B38B:69FA9058"},"id":"66fcad51-3a39-4e11-a9ad-b49fd0277cc0","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:50:43.030Z","parentId":"f2550565-49fc-4cd7-b041-717471ef70e3"}
